- `rotM (x.ofLp 1) (x.ofLp 2)` is a rotation matrix that rotates the vector `x` around the z-axis by an angle `θ = x₂`. The standard rotation matrix around the z-axis is:
  ```
  [ cos(θ)  -sin(θ)  0 ]
  [ sin(θ)   cos(θ)  0 ]
  [  0        0      1 ]
  ```
  So, `rotM (x₂)` applied to `x` (vector) would be:
  ```
  [ cos(x₂)  -sin(x₂)  0 ] [ x₁ ]
  [ sin(x₂)   cos(x₂)  0 ] [ x₂ ]
  [  0        0      1 ] [ x₃ ]
  ```
  This results in the vector `(cos(x₂)x₁ - sin(x₂)x₂, sin(x₂)x₁ + cos(x₂)x₂, x₃)`.
- `rotR (x.ofLp 0)` is a rotation matrix that rotates the vector `x` around the x-axis by an angle `φ = x₀`. The standard rotation matrix around the x-axis is:
